Reference-contexts: For these types of problems the predictive Bayesian approach seems appropriate for both design and analysis. <ref> (See, for example, Geisser, 1993) </ref> Other utility functions can be devised for designing experiments that take into account more specific problems. As an example of a choice of an appropriate utility function in a design problem, consider the issue of randomization. <p> As noted in section 1, prediction can be more important than inference in certain experiments. In quality control or in clinical trials there can be special concern in predicting future observations. In these cases the Bayesian approach uses predictive analysis <ref> (Geisser, 1993) </ref>. This can also be done for designing the experiment. The expected gain in Shannon information can be used for prediction too, but now interest is focused on the future observation y n+1 , rather than on the vector of parameters.
